 	<div id="main-article-info">

		
		
			<h1 itemprop="name headline"
								>Hangover restoratives and cures</h1>
		
					<p itemprop="description" id="stand-first"
				 class="stand-first-alone"                data-component="comp : r2 : Article : standfirst_cta"
			>It's impossible to shake off a hangover by sheer willpower, but foods and liquids can help. What's your remedy?</p>
		
		
  	</div>

  	  	    			<ul id="content-actions" class="share-links trackable-component" data-component="comp: r2: Share tools">
				                
    
	
		
												


    
    
    	
    	
    	

        <li class="full-line facebook">
        <span class="facebook-share">
            <a class="facebook-share-btn" href="http://www.facebook.com/dialog/feed?app_id=180444840287&amp;link=http://www.guardian.co.uk/lifeandstyle/wordofmouth/2012/jan/03/hangover-restoratives-and-cures&amp;display=popup&amp;redirect_uri=http://static-serve.appspot.com/static/facebook-share/callback.html&amp;show_error=false" data-href="http://www.guardian.co.uk/lifeandstyle/wordofmouth/2012/jan/03/hangover-restoratives-and-cures" data-link-name="Facebook Share">
                <span class="facebook-share-icon"></span>
                <span class="facebook-share-label">Share</span>
            </a>
        </span>
    </li>

    <li class="full-line">
	    	    	    	    	    	    <a href="http://twitter.com/share" class="twitter-share-button" data-url="http://gu.com/p/34a9g/tw" data-via="guardian" data-counturl="http://www.guardian.co.uk/lifeandstyle/wordofmouth/2012/jan/03/hangover-restoratives-and-cures" data-related="lifeandstyle" data-text="Hangover restoratives and cures ">Tweet this</a>
    </li>

                <li class="full-line google-plus" data-link-name="Google plus" >

    	
    <div class="g-plusone" data-size="medium" data-callback="trackGPlus"></div>

    </li>

    <li class="full-line linked-in" data-link-name="LinkedIn">
        <script type="IN/Share" data-counter="right" data-showzero="true" data-onsuccess="trackLinkedIn"></script>
    </li>

    <li class="full-line email" data-link-name="email this story">
       <a class="rollover send-email" href="mailto:?subject=From the Guardian: Hangover restoratives and cures&body=I thought you might be interested in this link from the Guardian: Hangover restoratives and cures - http://gu.com/p/34a9g/em"  title="Send to a friend" ><img src="http://static.guim.co.uk/static/fc767601364a8d5153b208ff2289c6ddaa7fad7a/common/images/icon-email.png" alt="" class="trail-icon" />Email</a>
    </li>
    
    
    

			</ul>
		
			</div>


<div id="content">

				
    				
                
                	    

    
    
        	    





		
										

        


    
        

        <div id="article-wrapper" >

        	
        			<div id="main-content-picture" itemscope itemprop="image" itemtype="http://schema.org/ImageObject">
							<img src="http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2011/12/22/1324574293035/Bloody-Mary-containing-to-007.jpg" width="460" height="276" alt="Bloody Mary, containing tomato juice, vodka, celery, pepper and Tabasco sauce"  itemprop="contentUrl representativeOfPage" />
										<div class="caption" itemprop="caption">A Bloody Mary, containing tomato juice, vodka, celery, pepper and Tabasco sauce. Photograph: Alamy</div>
					</div>
	
    <div id="article-body-blocks">
	    <p>Kingsley Amis, that imperishable drink – rather than drinks – writer, pointed out that a hangover takes two forms. These are the physical and metaphysical (PH and MH). Food taken on a hangover must address both, though the MH ("that ineffable compound of depression ... anxiety, self-hatred, sense of failure and fear for the future") is harder to tackle.</p><p>Alcohol lowers your blood sugar and makes you particularly hungry. That's why hungover people crave fat, sugar and carbs (those two are related, of course): they're the most efficient ways to take on calories. I often find the PH can be palliated with a lunchtime bowl of carbohydrates, particularly pasta, which helps to effect a restorative nap at around 3pm. Healthy, "minerally" foods are most useful for the MH, as is anything with a level of umami. A few food critics, writers and other industry insiders told me their favourite <a href="http://www.guardian.co.uk/lifeandstyle/hangover-cures" title="More from guardian.co.uk on Hangover cures">hangover cures</a>: their selection follows.</p><p><strong>Watermelon and lipton iced lemon tea</strong> <br /><a href="http://lizzieeatslondon.blogspot.com/">• Lizzie Mabbott</a>, food blogger</p><p>A sensible one, this. Watermelon contains lots of sugar (Weight Watchers are often surprised how many "points" this seemingly innocuous fruit contains), a great deal of water, and it certainly feels healthy. The crunchiness may be a challenge to especially tender heads, and those with problematic bowels should beware the high fibre content. I can't abide caffeine on a hangover, it makes me jittery and paranoid, but iced tea is probably OK. The overall virtuousness of this remedy will help the MH.</p><p><strong>Pork and century egg congee!</strong><br /><a href="http://www.feedthetang.com/">• Feed the Tang</a>, food blogger</p><p>I'll take your word for it.</p><p><strong>Lucozade and a bacon sandwich</strong><br /><a href="http://www.z-pr.com/">• Lucy Warne</a>, PR</p><p>Many people claim Lucozade as their secret weapon in fighting hangovers; apparently it works best when taken the night before. A bottle contains 21 teaspoons of sugar, however, which I think I'd struggle to sleep on no matter how squiffy. The <a href="http://www.telegraph.co.uk/science/science-news/5118283/Bacon-sandwich-really-does-cure-a-hangover.html">bacon sandwich needs no explanation</a>.</p><p><strong>Marmite and cheese on toast followed by ginger beer</strong><br /><a href="http://saltounite.wordpress.com/author/saltounite/">• Saltounite</a>, food blogger </p><p>An insightful combination that assaults the hangover on both fronts. Cheese on toast has a homely perfection and would be far better than some greasy pizza. The Marmite provides enriching salt and the deep, ineffable pleasure of concentrated umami to counteract the MH. (Alcohol also depletes B vitamins, which Marmite contains in abundance.) Ginger is a folkloric anti-emetic and stomach-settler.</p><p><strong>Lots and lots of miso soup</strong><br />• Charmaine Mok, Time Out restaurant critic</p><p>Miso soup is one of my favourite hangover cures, and I keep an emergency tub in the fridge for exactly that reason. Both PH and MH diminish at the sight of miso: the salt, the broth and the umami flavours respectively address the lack of minerals, dehydration and any sense of ill-being. I would never advise miso soup alone to cure a hangover, but it's well worth having in the arsenal. Charmaine recommends <a href="http://japancentre.com/items/2001">this brand</a>.</p><p><strong>A pint of fanta orange and a KFC Zinger Tower meal or dirty curry</strong><br />• Sharan Sunner, PR</p><p>Next stop: self-loathing.</p><p><strong>My gnocchi recipe which has so much cheese and carb loadage that you fall straight back to sleep again</strong><br /><a href="http://www.libertylondongirl.com">• Liberty London Girl</a>, food and fashion blogger</p><p>When <a href="http://www.libertylondongirl.com/2011/12/02/recipe-friday-llg-cooks-fried-gnocchi-with-mozzarella-cherry-tomatoes/">only carbs will do</a>: gnocchi fried with fresh tomatoes and clumps of mozzarella. No better way to bring on the 3pm nap (see earlier).</p><p><strong>Bloody mary. Fry-up</strong><br /><a href="http://londonfood.typepad.com/">• Ben Bush</a>, food blogger</p><p>As perfect a hangover cure as any I can think of, not least because it sounds relaxed, communal and Sunday morningish and will thus be as effective on the MH as the PH. The tomatoes contain lots of vitamins, the fat will speedily lead to a feeling of fullness, mushrooms, beans and tomato juice are semi-healthy, and then we have the magic of bacon. A note on hair of the dog: booze is of course an extremely effective hangover "cure", indeed the best I know of. But drinking extensively on a hangover is probably unwise.</p><p><strong>Nurofen, full fat coke, sausage and egg McMuffin, salt and vinegar crisps and a latte</strong><br /><a href="http://www.twelvepointfivepercent.com/">• Hugh Wright</a>, food blogger</p><p>Hugh addresses his hangover from a number of angles. A base layer of painkiller combines with sugar, caffeine and hydration: this is a combination for people who unluckily have to <em>do</em> something while hungover. Sausage and egg McMuffins appear regularly in online compendia of hangover remedies: I've never tried one but they look appropriately horrible. Are the crisps are de trop? Hot milk is wonderful on a hangover.</p><p>Several people I contacted claimed that bed, time and so on were the only true hangover cures. While it's impossible to shake off a hangover by sheer willpower, foods and liquids can certainly help to get rid of one. No doubt you have own recommendations – on a day like today, I'm sure many would benefit if you shared them.</p>
    </div>

						
	
		
            	    





		
										

        


        </div>
    
    
                
</div>

				
